Magi are combat-capable arcane practitioners trained at the Wizard's Keep near the Cinderteeth Mountains, an institution founded as explicit correction to the Spirebound Conclave's catastrophic lack of oversight. The Conclave was chartered during the Keeper Era's late decline to preserve dangerous magical knowledge — its Doctrine of Continuance held that no dangerous discovery should die with its keeper. When border wars severed supply routes, the Conclave reframed Continuance from scholarly ideal into survival engine: volunteers became condemned debtors and political prisoners transferred under sealed warrants countersigned by proto-civic institutions including predecessors of Midgaard's guild courts and Kowloon's Jade Magistracy. The Conclave's three factions — Ember Canon (will through suffering and fire), Prism Thesis (structure through crystal harmonics), and Pale Ledger (spirit imprinting and memory extraction) — competed through their experimental subjects rather than theoretical debate. Catastrophic collapse followed: seismic event, internal sabotage, and structural damage from crystal resonance experiments. The Wizard's Keep was founded in response: registry law compliance with every operation witnessed and recorded, the Triple-Ledger Rule requiring three independent witnesses and three separate archive records for significant operations, and multi-jurisdictional archive distribution preventing any single authority from controlling the documentation. The Keep's frontier militarization context — adjacent to Cinderteeth Mountains, ongoing volcanic instability, subsurface resonance effects — distinguishes magi from academic arcane practitioners: Keep training includes substantial practical combat application because practitioners who cannot defend themselves cannot do field research. Magi advance into Wizard (Axiomatic Schools formal proof) or Sorcerer (Chromatic Circle elemental synthesis) remort paths.

